<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-08-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-08-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="407" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to
                                    Mr. <persName type="to">Merrill</persName>.</hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 55.]</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-08-16"><hi rend="italic">August 16,
                                        1887</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have forwarded a copy of your
                                dispatch No. 132 of July 15, 1887, touching the presence of naval
                                vessels in Hawaiian waters, to the Secretary of the Navy, calling
                                his attention to your recommendation that an American man-of-war be
                                permitted to remain in that vicinity for several months, at
                                least.</p>
                            <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">T. F.
                                Bayard.</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>